Scenario Explanations: Core Concepts

1. Semantic Versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH)

To bring order to releases, software engineering relies on Semantic Versioning (SemVer) formatted as vX.Y.Z (e.g., v1.2.3):

MAJOR (1.0.0 → 2.0.0): Incompatible API changes or breaking updates.

MINOR (1.2.0 → 1.3.0): Adding new features in a backward-compatible 
manner.

PATCH (1.2.3 → 1.2.4): Backward-compatible bug fixes or minor hotfixes.

2. Branching Strategies & Team Complexity

Your branching strategy dictates how code flows from developer machines to production. The choice depends on team size and deployment velocity:

Trunk-Based Development (Best for fast/large teams): Developers commit short-lived feature branches directly into main. Heavy automated testing ensures stability.

GitHub Flow (Simple/Small teams): Clean and straightforward. Create a feature branch $\rightarrow$ open a Pull Request (PR) $\rightarrow$ merge to main $\rightarrow$ deploy.

GitFlow (Complex/Enterprise releases): Uses multiple long-lived branches (main, develop, release/*, hotfix/*). Best for strict release cycles, though heavier to manage.

3. Git Tags vs. Git Branches

Branch (main, feature/app): A moving pointer to the latest commit. Branches constantly change as developers add code.

Tag (v1.0.0): An immutable snapshot tied to one specific commit in history. It locks down an exact state of the infrastructure or code so nobody can accidentally overwrite or modify it.

4. Push Protection & Security Controls

To prevent unexpected or destructive changes in production infrastructure:

Push Protection: GitHub blocks commits containing exposed secrets (AWS keys, Docker tokens) before they land in the repository.

Branch Protection Rules: Requires Pull Request approvals, status checks (passing CI builds), and blocks force-pushes (git push --force) on main.

